# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: benjamin-gould-politician
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/benjamin-gould-politician] Gould was the eldest son of Ephraim Gould (c.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/benjamin-gould-politician] 1825 – 10 October 1891), draper, of Bowden and his wife Susannah, née Barnes (c.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/benjamin-gould-politician] 1827 – 14 November 1891). who emigrated to South Australia on the *Constance*, arriving at Port Adelaide in May 1848.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/benjamin-gould-politician] He was Mayor of Hindmarsh from December 1893 to July 1896 (E.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/benjamin-gould-politician] He was elected to the South Australian House of Assembly for the seat of West Torrens and sat from April 1887 to April 1893, his colleagues being Benjamin Nash followed by Thomas Henry Brooker.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/benjamin-gould-politician] He was for a time organist for the Way Memorial Church, Bowden, and for about 17 years a member of the Pirie Street Methodist Church choir.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/benjamin-gould-politician] He was leader of the Bowden Brass Band from 1885 to 1895.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/benjamin-gould-politician] He died at his home, Chief street, Brompton after a long illness.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/benjamin-gould-politician] *Former members of the Parliament of South Australia*.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/benjamin-nash] He was born in Birmingham and emigrated to Melbourne in 1857 but in July, after only a few months in the gold diggings, moved to Rundle Street, Adelaide and set up a tailoring business.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/benjamin-nash] He was prominent in the Voluntary Militia, and from 1858 to 1865 served with the West Adelaide Company under Colonel George Mayo.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/benjamin-nash] In 1859 he successfully tendered for the supply of the first uniforms for the Volunteer Military Force.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/benjamin-nash] In 1878 he was elected to the Walkerville District Council, and became its chairman.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/benjamin-nash] He was elected to the seat of West Torrens and sat from April 1887 to April 1890.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/benjamin-nash] He failed in his bid to be reelected, and died of kidney failure ten days later.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/benjamin-nash] He was buried in West Terrace Cemetery's Catholic section.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/benjamin-nash] He had converted to that faith around two years before his death.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/bowden-south-australia] The 'Village of Bowden' was established in 1839 by James Hurtle Fisher, who named it after his native village in Northamptonshire.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/bowden-south-australia] Bowden had a post office open from 1970 until 1991.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/bowden-south-australia] Before 1970 the office in the area was named *Ovingham*; after 1991 the *Brompton* office has provided postal services.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/bowden-south-australia] In October 2008, Premier Mike Rann and Infrastructure Minister Patrick Conlon announced the purchase of the 10-hectare Clipsal factory site in Bowden to become a new "green village".
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/bowden-south-australia] They announced plans for up to 1,500 medium- and high-density Green Star residential apartments, with retail outlets and commercial offices set around a town centre, for the former industrial site.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/bowden-south-australia] The $1 billion Bowden development was designed to be a "transport-oriented development"(TOD) as envisaged by *The 30-Year Plan for Greater Adelaide*.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/bowden-south-australia] At the on-site announcement, Mr Rann said the development was expected to take 12 to 15 years to complete.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/bowden-south-australia] In 2010, the State Government purchased the adjacent Origin Energy site (formerly Brompton Gasworks).
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/bowden-south-australia] Construction on the first stage and parks were officially opened in May 2013 by Premier Jay Weatherill.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/bowden-south-australia] Construction commenced on first residential dwellings in 2013.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/bowden-south-australia] First residents moved into their homes in 2014.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/bowden-south-australia] The suburb is primarily bounded by the Grange/Outer Harbor railway line, the Gawler railway line and Park Terrace.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/bowden-south-australia] The 2006 Census by the Australian Bureau of Statistics counted 648 persons in Bowden on census night.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/bowden-south-australia] Of these, 51.2% were male and 48.8% were female.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/bowden-south-australia] Within ten years, the 2016 Census recorded 911 people in Bowden, with 52% being male and 48% being female, and further increased to 1,808 people in 2021, with 51.1% recorded as male and 48.9% as female.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/bowden-south-australia] The majority of residents (60.8%) are of Australian birth, with other common census responses being England (4.6%), China (4.1%), Malaysia (2.0%), and India (1.5%), New Zealand (1.3%).
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/bowden-south-australia] Additionally, people of Aboriginal and/or Torres Strait Islander descent made up 1.2% of the suburb.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/bowden-south-australia] In terms of religious affiliation, 58.2% of residents attributed themselves to being irreligious, 11.4% attributed themselves to being Catholic, 3.7% attributed themselves to be Anglican, and 2.9% attributed themselves to being Muslim.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/bowden-south-australia] Bowden is part of Hindmarsh Ward in the City of Charles Sturt local government area, being represented in that council by Paul Alexandrides and Alice Campbell.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/bowden-south-australia] Bowden lies in the state electoral district of Croydon and the federal electoral division of Adelaide.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/bowden-south-australia] The suburb is represented in the South Australian House of Assembly by Peter Malinauskas and federally by Steve Georganas.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/bowden-south-australia] The local newspaper is the *Weekly Times Messenger*.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/bowden-south-australia] Adelaide Bike Kitchen is a community-run group on Gibson Street that teaches people to maintain or build their own bicycles.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/bowden-south-australia] Uniting Care Wesley Bowden is charity that helps people and families, and is located at Gibson Street.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/bowden-south-australia] The Bowden Brompton Community Centre is based at 19 Green Street, Brompton.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/bowden-south-australia] Bowden is serviced by Torrens Road, Park Terrace and Hawker Street.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/bowden-south-australia] Many of the local streets were established in the 19th century.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/bowden-south-australia] Consequently, roadways tend to be narrow and quiet with a small volume of traffic.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/bowden-south-australia] Bowden's new streets are designed to be 'walkable' and shared by vehicles, bicycles and people.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/bowden-south-australia] With the new development, the suburb is starting to see a lot more pop-up street art and curbless, tree-lined streets furnished with street furniture on footpaths.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/bowden-south-australia] Bowden is serviced by public transport run by the Adelaide Metro.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/bowden-south-australia] The tram line runs between the Adelaide Entertainment Centre to Glenelg with Park n Ride facilities available at the Entertainment Centre tram stop.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/bowden-south-australia] The tram runs for free when travelling between the Entertainment Centre stop and South Terrace stop in Adelaide's central business district.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/bowden-south-australia] The following train services run on the eastern and southern boundaries of the suburb.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] Brompton is on the land of the Kaurna People, an area that stretches from Port Broughton to Cape Jervis.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] Prior to the colonisation of South Australia in 1836, the Kaurna people managed and lived off the land and waterways of the region.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] Neighbouring the areas that became the villages of Bowden and Brompton, "Hindmarsh Town" was established in 1838 as South Australia's first secondary town outside of Adelaide.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] This was criticised for 'disfiguring' Wakefield's theory of 'concentrated settlement' by creating a population centre outside the city Adelaide.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] Moreover, Hindmarsh Town was intended to be an independent working class town, managed by a committee of management consisting of skilled workers and lower middle class settlers.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] Bowden was established as a neighbouring village to Hindmarsh Town in 1839.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] Brompton was established ten years later, in June 1849, when William Sanders and William Paxton subdivided section 355 of the Hundred of Yatala.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] The name Brompton comes from Yorkshire, England where Willam Paxton was born.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] The Bowden and Brompton villages had notably narrower streets and smaller allotments compared to Hindmarsh, particularly in Bowden.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] Both new villages were populated by working class settlers, due to the small parcels of land and nearby industries.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] In the 1850s the three villages of Bowden, Brompton and Hindmarsh became the centres of population, commerce and industry of the Hindmarsh district.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] Land ownership was concentrated to a small number of individuals who also dominated the economic, civic and social affairs of the area.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] This group of "local establishment" further profited from subdividing allotments and building cottages for rental by labourers and poor people.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] Brickmaking was a common industry in Brompton, due to an abundance of clay in the area and water available from the River Torrens.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] The Hocking Brothers established a brickfield on about three acres of land in Brompton in the mid-1850s, and by 1869 the site employed seven men and produced about 13,000 bricks a week.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] To meet the heating and lighting needs of the emerging colony of South Australia, the SA Gas Company established the Brompton Gassworks, on Chief Street, Brompton.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] The glasswork started operating in 1863 by burning black coal in furnaces to produce coal gas.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] By-products were tar, weed poison and coke.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] This has been described as "the first major step in converting a semi-rural village into a manufacturing township".
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] The site became a significant employer of local residents over the next 140 years, dominating the landscape with its high chimneys and enormous stone and brick structure.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] At the time, some people considered coal burning as providing health benefits.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] People would bring their asthmatic children to the gasworks and walk them around, believing that the burning of coal cleared the air.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] By 1865, the number of houses in Brompton had remained at about 70, however there were now eight shops, 11 brickyards, a chapel, and the glassworks.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] In 1875, "Paddy" Coglin subdivided land which became Brompton Park (now part of Brompton) and Ridleyton North, from an extensive block of land that he purchased on Coglin Street.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] The subdivision was intended to house the 'late arrivals from England' and for what Coglin described as access to the 'inexhaustible stores of incomparable brick-clay'.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] The small size of the residential divisions were condemned as 'pocket-handkerchief allotments', and many backyards were below street level with no drainage.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] When it rained, muddy streets were washed in with household refuse, creating stagnant pools in backyards.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] This contributed to the deaths of many children from typhoid.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] In the early years, there was also no water supply to Brompton Park, and residents had to walk to the Bowden railway station to collect water, which was only available for one hour in the morning and one hour in the afternoon, restricting availability for working people.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] An economic boom in the late 1870s expanded the brickyards in the Brompton area, and in 1882 the Metropolitan Brick Company was formed.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] The company acquired 28 acres of land at Brompton Park to obtain clay and produce bricks.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] In 1884, the Hoffman kiln was built on Hawker Street, Brompton, which allowed for continuous firing, wasting less fuel and recycling of waste heat.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] The kiln held 16 chambers and had a capacity for firing 320,000 bricks a day.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] In 1883, Brompton was known as the area where the brick carriers congregated.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] The brickmakers were adverse to fencing the pug holes leftover from brick-making industry, which created a safety hazard for local people, especially in winter when they became lakes.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] The suburb lies between Torrens Road and the Grange/Outer Harbor railway line and is bordered by Torrens Road at its northern end.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] The 2016 Census by the Australian Bureau of Statistics counted 3,537 persons in Brompton on census night.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] Of these, 48.4% were male and 51.6% were female.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] The majority of residents (60.4%) are of Australian birth, with other common census responses being China (5.7%), Greece (4.8%), England (3.3%), Vietnam (1.9%), and India (1.4).
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] In terms of religious affiliation, 41.4% of residents attributed themselves to being irreligious, 15.8% attributed themselves to being Catholic, 8.5% attributed themselves to be Eastern Orthodox, and 6.1% attributed themselves to being Anglican.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] Within Brompton, 91.4% of the residents were employed, with the remaining 8.6% being unemployed.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] Brompton is part of Hindmarsh Ward in the City of Charles Sturt local government area, being represented in that council by members Alice Campbell and Katriona Kinsella.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] Brompton lies in the state electoral district of Croydon and the federal electoral division of Adelaide.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] It was established in 1972 by a community group for residents to address community and housing issues.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] Additionally, Brompton also contains the Adelaide Croatian Club.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] Bowden Brompton Community School is located on Torrens Road and Immaculate Heart of Mary School is located on East Street.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] The Brompton Hotel and the Excelsior Hotel are in the suburb.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] There are several parks in Brompton, the largest of which is **Josiah Mitton Reserve**, between Wood Avenue and Burley Griffin Boulevard.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] The reserve includes the Hindmarsh Incinerator, designed by Walter Burley Griffin in 1935.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] Completed in 1936, it is one of his two buildings in SA listed as among the 120 nationally significant 20th-century buildings in South Australia, the other being the Thebarton Incinerator at Thebarton.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] Other notable parks within Brompton include **Stormrage Reserve**, **Thomas Harkness Reserve**, and **Ethelbert Reserve**.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] From 1949 until 1979, Brompton was the home to the world-famous Rowley Park Speedway located on the corner of Torrens Road and Coglin Street.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] Rowley Park was a 358 metres (392 yards) dirt track speedway built in the old Brompton Brick Pits and operated 23 meetings per season (usually October to April) on Friday nights and was capable of holding over 10,000 spectators.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] The speedway hosted numerous Australian and South Australian speedway championships through its history.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] From 1954 until 1973, the speedway was promoted by leading Adelaide identity Kym Bonython who made Rowley Park 'the' place to be in Adelaide on a Friday night during summer.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] Rowley Park closed on 4 April 1979 and is now the site of the Kym Bonython housing estate.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] In 1965, Rowley Park was the site of Australia's first Demolition derby.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] Brompton is primarily serviced by Torrens Road, which connects the suburb to Adelaide city centre.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] Hawker Street cuts through the centre of the suburb.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] Prior to 1956, a tram operated down Hawker street, connecting to the Cheltenham races and Croydon cinema.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] In the 1980s Hawker street had fallen into such a poor state it was considered the worst street in Adelaide.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] Consequently, roadways tend to be narrow and, with a small volume of traffic, quiet.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] Brompton is serviced by public transport run by the Adelaide Metro.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] There is no train stop in Ridleyton but the Grange and Outer Harbor railway lines pass nearby.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/brompton-south-australia] On the Gawler railway line the closest station is Ovingham.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/electoral-district-of-west-torrens] West Torrens has had several incarnations, first as a Legislative Council district, then four times as a South Australian House of Assembly electoral district.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/evening-journal-adelaide] Its former names were ***The Evening Journal*** (1869–1912) and ***The Journal*** (1912–1923), with the Saturday edition called ***The Saturday Journal*** until 1929.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/evening-journal-adelaide] News Limited was established in 1923 by James Edward Davidson, when he purchased the Broken Hill *Barrier Miner* and the Port Pirie *Recorder*.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/evening-journal-adelaide] He then went on to purchase *The Journal* and Adelaide's weekly sports-focussed *Mail* in May 1923.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/evening-journal-adelaide] On 24 July 1923, *The Journal* was renamed *The News* (restarting at Volume 1, Issue 1), with the Saturday edition being retained as *The Saturday Journal* (which continued to be published until 1929).
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/evening-journal-adelaide] In 1923, the new newspaper had a circulation of 30,000, and by 1953, it had a daily readership of 106,000.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/evening-journal-adelaide] In early 1948, the regular format was changed from broadsheet to tabloid.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/evening-journal-adelaide] In 1933, a controlling stake was taken by *The Advertiser* and managed by *The Herald and Weekly Times*.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/evening-journal-adelaide] *HWT* sold off its stake in 1949, allowing Sir Keith Murdoch to acquire a major interest in the company and to assume control of the paper in 1951.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/evening-journal-adelaide] *The News* became the main asset passed upon his death in 1952 to his son Rupert Murdoch.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/evening-journal-adelaide] It was the latter's first media interest and commenced the foundation of what was to become the international media conglomerate, News Corporation.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/evening-journal-adelaide] On 6 February 1954, *The Mail* was renamed *SA Sunday Mail* and then *Sunday Mail* in 1955.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/evening-journal-adelaide] On 28 August 1976, the final Saturday issue of *The News* was published.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/evening-journal-adelaide] Murdoch later acquired the city's other local newspaper, the morning daily broadsheet, *The Advertiser,* in 1987.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/evening-journal-adelaide] Murdoch sold *The News* that year to Northern Star Holdings, and many of its journalists moved to *The Advertiser*.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/evening-journal-adelaide] However, in the face of continuing losses brought about by the competition of television and the decline of use of public transport and given the more prominent existence of *The Advertiser,* *The News* (then Australia’s last evening newspaper) was stopped on 27 March 1992.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The **Parliament of South Australia** is the bicameral legislature of the Australian state of South Australia.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] It consists of the 47-seat House of Assembly (lower house) and the 22-seat Legislative Council (upper house).
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] General elections are held every 4 years, with all of the lower house and half of the upper house filled at each election.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] It follows a Westminster system of parliamentary government with the executive branch required to both sit in parliament and hold the confidence of the House of Assembly.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The parliament is based at Parliament House on North Terrace in the state capital of Adelaide.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Unlike the federal parliament and the parliaments of most other states, the South Australian Constitution does not define the parliament as including either the monarch or the governor of South Australia as one of its constituent parts.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] However, the constitution also vests legislative power in the state's governor acting with the advice and consent of both houses of parliament, making the role of the governor effectively the same as those of the other states.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The parliament may make laws for any matter within South Australia, subject to the Constitution of South Australia.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Its power is further limited by the ability for the federal parliament to override it in some circumstances, subject to the Constitution of Australia.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Similarly, the Supreme Court of South Australia, and ultimately the High Court of Australia, provides judicial oversight of parliament.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The parliament is also vested with other powers, such as the means to investigate matters, conduct research and summon witnesses.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] At the founding of the Province of South Australia under the *South Australia Act 1834*, governance of the new colony was divided between the Governor of South Australia and a Resident Commissioner, who reported to a new body known as the *South Australian Colonization Commission*.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Under this arrangement, there was also a governing Council comprising the Governor, the Judge or Chief Justice, the Colonial Secretary, the Advocate-General and the Resident Commissioner, with broad legislative and executive powers including the imposition of rates, duties, and taxes.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] This council was sometimes referred to as the "Legislative Council".
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Confusion and dispute about the division of power between the two roles led to the *South Australia Government Act 1838*, which combined the role of Resident Commissioner with that of the Governor.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] In 1842, the *South Australia Act 1842* was passed in order to replace the South Australian Colonisation Commission appointed in 1834 with a more standard British model of government, with a Governor advised by a Legislative Council.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The 1842 Act gave the British Government, which was responsible for appointing a Governor and at least seven other officers to the Legislative Council, full control of South Australia as a Crown Colony, after financial mismanagement by the first administration had nearly bankrupted the colony.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] This new Legislative Council was the first true parliamentary body in South Australia.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The Act also made provision for a commission to initiate the establishment of democratic government, electoral districts, requirements for voting rights, and terms of office.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Although the old governing Council advising the Governor met at Government House, this new Legislative Council met at a new purpose built chamber on North Terrace.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] This chamber eventually grew into what is now known as "Old Parliament House".
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] In 1851 elections for the Legislative Council were held.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The new Council consisted of 24 members, four official (filling what would be today ministerial positions) and four non-official members, both nominated by the governor on behalf of the Crown, and 16 elected members chosen from single-member districts.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The right to vote for these positions was not universal, however, being limited to propertied men.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] In addition, the reforms meant that the Governor no longer oversaw proceedings, with the role being filled by a Speaker who had been elected by the members.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] In 1853 the Legislative Council sent London a *Parliament Act 1853* that provided for a new constitution that established a bicameral parliament with an elected lower house and an upper house made up of members nominated for life.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The colonists were mistakenly under the impression that only such a scheme would be acceptable to the British Government.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The Governor, Sir Henry Young, had been advised that this was not the case but he kept this information to himself.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The colonists were furious and 5,000 petitioned Westminster to give them two elected houses.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The offending constitution was returned and in 1855, a new Legislative Council was elected with a mandate to establish something far more radical and democratic than had been seen in the British Empire before.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] This was expressed by the *Constitution Act 1856* (headed "1855–6: No.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] 2" and followed by the long title "An Act to establish a Constitution for South Australia, and to grant a Civil List to Her Majesty") establishing the constitution of the Parliament of the Province of South Australia.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] This Constitution Act provided for a bicameral parliament with full authority to enact laws, apart from a few Acts requiring the monarch's personal Royal Assent.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The 18-member Legislative Council was elected by property owners only, while the 36-member House of Assembly was elected by a full male franchise.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The Act also provided for a system of responsible government, where the members of the executive branch must sit in parliament and, by convention, can only remain in office while they hold the confidence of a majority of the members of the House of Assembly.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] It was the first Constitution in the Australian colonies to provide "manhood" suffrage.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The adoption of the "one man, one vote" principle also removed the ability of voters to vote in any electorate in which they owned property.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The Act also defined the rules of tenure for the parliamentarians.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Later in 1856, in preparation for responsible government, the old Legislative Council passed an Electoral Act providing for the secret ballot system of voting to be used for the new parliament, also known as the Australian Ballot.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The first bicameral parliament of South Australia was elected on 9 March 1857, with Boyle Travers Finniss as the inaugural Premier of South Australia responsible to parliament.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The parliament first sat on 22 April 1857.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Until 1887, membership of parliament was an unpaid position as members were expected to be able to support themselves through other means.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] This changed with the passage of the *Payment of Members Act 1887* that set an annual salary of 200 pounds for members of both Houses who were not ministers.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] This rate has subsequently continued to evolve with the rate now set by an independent remuneration tribunal.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] In 1889, the House of Assembly moved out of the original Parliament House and took up residence in a new building constructed next door.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Due to costs, this "New Parliament House" would remain unfinished for 50 years while the Legislative Council continued to be housed in the original Parliament House.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Women gained the right to vote and stand for election in 1895, taking effect at the 1896 election.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Once passed, South Australia become the fourth state in the world to give women the vote and the first to give women the right to be elected to parliament.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] South Australia became a state of the Commonwealth of Australia in 1901, following a vote to federate with the other British colonies of Australia.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] One consequence of federation was that the powers of the Parliament of South Australia were limited by the provisions of the Constitution of Australia, with some powers transferred to the federal parliament.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Another consequence was a bit of a "brain drain", with many of the parliament's most prominent members moving to the federal sphere.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] From 1857 to 1933, the House of Assembly was elected from multi-member districts, commonly known as "seats," with each district returning between one and six members.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The size of the Assembly grew during the colonial period—36 members from 1857 to 1875, 46 members from 1875 to 1884, 52 members from 1884 to 1890, 54 members from 1890 to 1902.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] In response to the Federation of Australia, the House of Assembly was reduced to 42 members from 1902 to 1912 and 40 members from 1912 to 1915 after the Northern Territory was ceded to federal administration.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] From 1915 to 1938 the size was again increased to 46 members.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The Legislative Council half of the "New Parliament House" was finally completed in 1939, 50 years after the House of Assembly portion of the building.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] One distinctive aspect of the history of the South Australian parliament was the "Playmander", a pro-rural electoral malapportionment introduced by the incumbent Liberal and Country League (LCL) government, and in place for 32 years from 1936 to 1968.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The already entrenched rural overweighting was increased to a 2:1 ratio, the number of MPs was reduced to 39 and the multi-member seats were abandoned for single-member seats.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The House of Assembly now consisted of 26 low-population rural seats, which due to population shifts, were holding up to a 10-to-1 advantage over the 13 high-population metropolitan seats, even though rural seats contained only a third of South Australia's population.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] At the peak of the malapportionment in 1968, the rural seat of Frome had 4,500 formal votes, while the metropolitan seat of Enfield had 42,000 formal votes.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Labor managed to win enough parliamentary seats to form government just once during the Playmander against the odds − in 1965.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Labor won comprehensive majorities of the statewide two-party vote whilst failing to form government in 1944, 1953, 1962 and 1968.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] More equitable boundaries were subsequently put in place following the 1968 (with the House increased to 47 members), 1975, and 1989 elections.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Since 1975, the distribution of the 47 electoral boundaries has been set by the South Australian Electoral Districts Boundaries Commission, an independent body.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Since a referendum in 1991, boundaries have been redistributed after each election.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Previously they were redistributed after every third election.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] There are currently 34 in the Adelaide metropolitan area and 13 in rural areas.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] These seats are intended to represent approximately the same population in each electorate.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The Legislative Council's numbers and electoral makeup have also varied over time.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] From the inception of responsible government to 1882, it had 18 members elected by a single colony-wide district, with the scheme originally set up so that 6 members would be elected every 4 years to serve a 12 year term.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] In 1882, the single colony-wide district was split into 4 electoral districts which were drawn with a heavy bias in favour of rural areas in place.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The new scheme was set up so that half of the Council was being elected each election.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Originally these electoral districts were the "Central District", the "Southern District", the "North-Eastern District" and the "Northern District", with each being represented by 6 members each.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] From 1902, the Central District continued to be represented by 6 members, while the rural districts were reduced to 4 members each.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The North-Eastern District was replaced by the "Midland District" from the 1910 election and in 1915 the Central District was split in half and became the "Central District No.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] 2", each being represented by 4 members.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] As for the size of the Council as a whole, from 1882 until 1902 it had 24 members; until 1915, 18 members; and until 1975, 20 members.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] From 1975, the Council size was increased to 22 members, with half (11) to be elected at each election by the entire state voting as one electorate.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Although the lower house had universal suffrage from 1895, the upper house, the Legislative Council, remained the domain of property owners until the Labor government of Don Dunstan managed to achieve reform of the chamber in 1973.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] At the same time, the franchise was also extended to ministers of religion, school head teachers, postmasters, railway stationmasters, and the officer in charge of a police station.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] A further extension of the franchise came in 1913, when the qualification of an occupier of a dwelling house was altered to include any inhabitant occupier, whether owner or tenant.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] In 1918, the right to vote for members of the upper house was extended to all those who had served in armed forced in the First World War.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] This was subsequently extended to Second World War veterans in 1940 and in 1969, it was simplified to apply to all Australian war veterans regardless of the war they served in.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] In 1969, the franchise was granted to any person who owned or rented property, regardless of the value of the property.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Further, the franchise was extended to the wedded spouse of the owner or renter.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Finally in 1973, all property qualifications were removed and the Council became a body elected via proportional representation by a single state-wide electorate from the same universal franchise as the House of Assembly.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Since the following 1975 South Australian state election, no one party has had control of the state's upper house with the balance of power controlled by a variety of minor parties and independents.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Originally, the electoral system for both houses was a form of plurality voting, where each voter is given as many votes as there are candidates to be elected.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] From 1929, this was changed to instant-runoff voting, with multi-member districts using the preferential block voting variant of the system.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] In 1973, as part of the reforms to the upper house, the Legislative Council switched to using a party list form of proportional representation voting that was subsequently changed to the single transferable vote in 1982.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] From 1985 until 2017, the Legislative Council also used a form of Group voting tickets similar to that used in the Senate at the time.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] This enabled voters to choose between voting 'above the line' (for a single party preference ticket that ranked all candidates on the ballot paper in the party's preferred order) or 'below the line' and number all candidates in order of preference, on the ballot paper.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Today, the House of Assembly continues to use instant-runoff voting with compulsory preferences.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Compulsory voting was introduced for the House of Assembly in 1942 and for the Legislative Council in 1985.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Elections were held every 3 years until 1985 (with a brief flirtation with 5 year terms for the House of Assembly in the 1933-1938 parliament), when the parliament switched to 4 year terms, meaning 8 year terms for the upper house.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Beginning in 2006, election dates have been fixed at the third Saturday in March of every fourth year.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The House of Assembly (or "lower house") is made up of 47 members who are each elected by the full-preference instant-runoff voting system in single-member electorates.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Each of the 47 electoral districts (electorates) contains approximately the same number of voters.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Casual vacancies, when a member retires or dies in office mid-term, are filled by a by-election in that member's district.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Since 1975, the distribution of electoral boundaries has been set by the South Australian Electoral Districts Boundaries Commission, an independent body.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Government is formed in the House of Assembly by the leader of the party or coalition who can demonstrate they have the support of the majority of the House, and is called upon by the Governor to form government.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The leader of the government becomes the Premier.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The House is presided over by a Speaker, who, as of the passage of the *Constitution (Independent Speaker) Amendment Act 2021*, is constitutionally banned from being a member of a registered political party outside of a "relevant election period".
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] At the 2014 election for example, although the statewide two-party vote (2PP) was 47.0% Labor v 53.0% Liberal, the metropolitan area recorded a 2PP of 51.5% Labor v 48.5% Liberal.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The term for the House of Assembly is a fixed 4-year term but the state Constitution does allow the Governor to dissolve the House early and call for a fresh general election under certain circumstances.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] These are: If the House passes a motion of no confidence in the government, the House defeats a motion of confidence in the government, or if a bill that has been designated by the House as a "bill of special importance" is passed by the House of Assembly but is rejected by the Legislative Council.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The House of Assembly can also be dissolved early together with the full Legislative Council in what is known as a double dissolution in order to resolve deadlocks between the two Houses.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The circumstances for such a double dissolution are outlined below.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The Legislative Council (or "upper house") is made up of 22 councillors (MLCs) who are elected for the entire state by the Proportional Representation single transferable voting system (with optional preferential voting) to serve for a term that is usually 8 years.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Elections for the Legislative Council are staggered so that 11 seats are up for re-election every 4 years, at the same time as House of Assembly elections.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Legislative Councillors may serve shorter or longer terms than the usual 8 years in the event of an early dissolution of the House of Assembly.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] If half the chamber has served at least 6 years at the time of a dissolution, then they go up for election, but if all Legislative Councillors have served less than 6 years, only the House of Assembly faces the people.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] In the event of a casual vacancy, members of the Legislative Council are filled by an assembly of the members of both houses of parliament.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] If the member whose seat has become vacant was elected as a member of a political party, the assembly must, if possible, replace them with a nominated member of that party.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The Legislative Council has almost equal powers to the House of Assembly.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The only difference is that the upper house does not have the ability to initiate or amend bills that appropriate money or levy taxes.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The Council may still request amendments to these bills and retains the right to reject money bills that it disagrees with.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The primary function of the Legislative Council is to review legislation which has been passed by the House of Assembly.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] This can cause tensions between the government and the Legislative Council, which may be viewed by the former as obstructionist if it rejects key legislation, as can happen at times when the electoral makeup of the two Houses are different.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Another important function of the upper house is to scrutinise government activity, which it does both in the chamber and through committees.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] As Legislative Councillors have been elected using proportional representation since the mid-1970s, the chamber features a multitude of parties vying for power.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] A government or opposition majority in the upper house has been unachievable since the introduction of this system, with the balance of power being held by a number of minor parties and independents.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] In the event that there is a conflict between the two Houses over legislation, the South Australian Constitution lays out a mechanism for how these deadlocks can be resolved.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] This procedure is known as a double dissolution.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] As the upper house consists of 22 members, with 11 elected statewide at each general election for an 8-year term at a quota of 8.33%, this would result in an election for all 22 members at a quota of 4.35%.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] In the event of a double dissolution election, the 11 Legislative Councillors that would not have won their seats under an ordinary election go up for re-election at the first general election after only serving 3 years, rather than the usual 6 years.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Although it has been threatened, this South Australian double dissolution procedure has never been used.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Although the practice has mostly fallen out of favour in other parliaments that use a bicameral Westminster system, the South Australian parliament still regularly appoints a "Conference of Managers" from each House to negotiate compromises on disputed bills in private.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The Conference Managers then prepare a report of recommendations that is submitted to both Houses.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Salaries of South Australian Members of Parliament (MPs), which include all Legislative Councillors and Members of the House of Assembly, are tied by the *Parliamentary Remuneration Act 1990* (SA) to those of Australian Federal MPs, less A$42,000.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] An independent remuneration tribunal sets the Federal base salaries.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Additional salary (payable to MPs who are also Ministers of office holders).
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Common allowance (which replaced travel allowances).
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Electorate allowance (for the provision of staff and resources.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Non-monetary benefits (such as a private motor vehicle).
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Ministers and office holders, such as the Leader of the Opposition, the Speaker of the House, and the President of the Council, are entitled to additional salary, which is set by the *Parliamentary Remuneration Act 1990* (SA).
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] As an example, the Leader of the Opposition is entitled to an additional 75% of the A$197,270 (2025) base salary, which is an additional $147,953, totalling an annual salary of $345,223 (rounded to the nearest dollar).
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] As of the passage of the *First Nations Voice Act 2023* in March 2023, South Australia also has an Aboriginal Voice to Parliament able to represent South Australia's Aboriginal population to the state parliament and government.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The Act was launched in a ceremony led by premier Peter Malinauskas, who acknowledged the work done by Attorney-General and Aboriginal Affairs Minister Kyam Maher, and First Nations Commissioner Dale Agius, to achieve the passing of the bill.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] A large crowd attended despite rainy weather, and Major "Moogy" Sumner spoke, danced, and performed the Welcome to Country.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The state is divided into six regions, whose Aboriginal voters will, at each state election, elect a "Local Voice" with gender parity.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] These local voices then elect one male and one female member each to be their joint presiding officers and sit on the "State First Nations Voice".
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The State Voice then in turn elects its own male and female joint presiding officers who have the right to enter either house of parliament to make speeches on bills that are of interest to the First Nations peoples in South Australia.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] They do not have the ability to vote on legislation.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The State Voice can also address state cabinet and government departments.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Members of the South Australian upper and lower houses with over 30 years of service.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The longest serving current member of Parliament is Tom Koutsantonis, who was elected to State Parliament in 1997 at age 26.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] The seat of the Parliament of South Australia is Parliament House in the state capital of Adelaide.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Parliament House sits on the North-Western corner of the intersection of King William Street and North Terrace.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] It was built to replace the adjacent and overcrowded Parliament House, now referred to as "Old Parliament House", which dated from 1843 with extensions in 1857.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/parliament-of-south-australia] Due to financial constraints, the current Parliament House was constructed in stages over 65 years from 1874 to 1939.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/pilgrim-uniting-church] Social justice, as articulated by the Uniting Church in Australia in the inaugural Statement to the Nation (1977), and the Statement to the Nation (1988) for Australia's Bicentennial celebrations, is at the basis of the church's work.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/pilgrim-uniting-church] Pilgrim offers music programs to the public, and has the largest organ in Adelaide.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/pilgrim-uniting-church] The congregation was originally at the Gawler Place Wesleyan Chapel.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/pilgrim-uniting-church] The first minister at the Pirie Street site was Daniel Draper.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/pilgrim-uniting-church] The first service was held on 19 October 1852.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/pilgrim-uniting-church] William Bowen Chinner was organist and choirmaster at Pirie Street from 1869 to around 1899.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/pilgrim-uniting-church] His nephew Norman Chinner filled the same positions from 1939.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/pilgrim-uniting-church] The first Congregational chapel in South Australia was a temporary structure on North Terrace.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/pilgrim-uniting-church] George Strickland Kingston was the architect for a building in Freeman Street (now Gawler Place), with the congregation then moving to the Flinders Street site.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/pilgrim-uniting-church] Stow Memorial Church, at 12 Flinders Street, Adelaide, was named in memory of the Reverend Thomas Quinton Stow, who had officiated at the first service in a tent on Adelaide's Park Lands in October 1837.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/pilgrim-uniting-church] The foundation stone was laid on 7 February 1865 and the inaugural worship service was held on 12 April 1867.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/pilgrim-uniting-church] The first minister was Cadwallader William Evan.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/pilgrim-uniting-church] The organist, who served for 45 years, was James Shakespeare.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/pilgrim-uniting-church] Pirie Street Methodist and Stow Memorial congregations united on 1 June 1969 to form the Union Church in the City.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/pilgrim-uniting-church] In November 1975 the church changed its name to become Pilgrim Church.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/pilgrim-uniting-church] The congregation joined the Uniting Church at its inauguration in 1977.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/pilgrim-uniting-church] The foundation stone for the Pirie Street Wesleyan Chapel was laid on 15 July 1850.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/pilgrim-uniting-church] The church was designed by Henry Stuckey.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/pilgrim-uniting-church] Completion of the building, after Henry Stuckey's death in 1851, was under the supervision of Edmund Wright.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/pilgrim-uniting-church] After the merger of the two congregations the building was bought by the Adelaide City Council and demolished in 1976.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/pilgrim-uniting-church] Wright was also the architect of the Methodist Meeting Hall, located between the Pirie Street and Flinders Street churches.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/pilgrim-uniting-church] The hall was built in 1862 and is the only remaining part of the Pirie Street property and is now part of the Adelaide Town Hall complex.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/pilgrim-uniting-church] The foundation stone of Stow Memorial Church, at 12 Flinders Street, Adelaide, was laid on 7 February 1865.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/pilgrim-uniting-church] It was designed in the Gothic Revival style by Robert George Thomas, who was among the first colonists, arriving in South Australia in 1836 aged 16 years.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/pilgrim-uniting-church] The organ in the Flinders Street building was initially installed in 1855 in the Pirie Street building with that from Flinders Street being sold to St John's Lutheran Church in Malvern.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/pilgrim-uniting-church] Improvements over the years have made it the largest organ in the state of South Australia.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/pilgrim-uniting-church] In August 2022, the City of Adelaide renamed the laneway adjacent to the church, formerly Pilgrim Lane, to Paul Kelly Lane, after Paul Kelly, a well-known musician who grew up in Norwood.
[src:benjamin-gould-politician/pilgrim-uniting-church] This was the fourth such renaming by the council, to honour musicians associated with the city.
